com.apriori.collections

Class ArrayListGrowableArray<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.apriori.collections.ArrayListGrowableArray<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type of element in the array
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    GrowableArray<T>, SizedIterable<T>, Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<T>

    public class ArrayListGrowableArray<T>
extends Object
implements GrowableArray<T>, Serializable, Cloneable
    A simple growable array that is backed by an ArrayList. This implementation basically doubles the underlying array capacity when it gets full. This implementation does not automatically shrink the underlying array, instead requiring callers to use trimToSize() to reduce the object's memory footprint.

    Because of the array-doubling technique and the fact that memory must be explicitly reclaimed after shrinking, this implementation can waste O(n) memory. Also, the array-doubling requires allocation of and then copying into a new (potentially very large) array. So, although amortized runtime complexity for growing the array by one is constant, the worst case is linear when it must perform a doubling.

    Despite these disadvantages, constant factors for random access operations are very low, and the use of a single underlying array is very cache-friendly. Also, the average case order of wasted memory is often much lower than the worst case. So this makes it a very high-performing implementation under many conditions.

      • trimToSize

        public void trimToSize()
        Trims the underlying array to be the same length as the size of this growable array. This reduces wasted memory at the expense of (potentially) having to create a new, smaller array first (into which the contents are copied).
